properties.headline: Wind Chill Advisory issued January 15 at 2:56PM CST until January 16 at 10:00AM CST by NWS Duluth MN
properties.description:
...SNOW ENDING THIS EVENING FOLLOWED BY DANGEROUS COLD TONIGHT...
...HEAVY SNOW EXPECTED FRIDAY THROUGH SATURDAY...

.Light snow over the Northland today will come to an end from west
to east this evening. Additional snowfall amounts of up to an
inch are possible this evening. Lingering Lake Effect snow will
continue for parts of the South Shore of Lake Superior, where an
additional 1 to 3 inches are possible. Once the snow ends and
skies clear, temperatures will turn sharply colder, with bitter
cold wind chill temperatures expected as northwest winds continue
tonight. Wind chill values of 20 to 35 below zero are expected.
Snow returns to the forecast for Friday through Saturday, with
widespread accumulating snow, with snowfall amounts of 5 to 10
inches possible.

* WHAT...For the Winter Weather Advisory, snow. Additional snow
accumulations of up to two inches this evening. For the Wind
Chill Advisory, very cold wind chills expected. Wind chills as
low as 25 below zero. For the Winter Storm Watch, heavy mixed
precipitation possible. Total snow accumulations of 5 to 9
inches and ice accumulations of a light glaze possible.

* WHERE...Douglas, Bayfield, Burnett, Washburn, Sawyer and Price
Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band.

* WHEN...For the Winter Weather Advisory, until 6 PM CST this
evening. For the Wind Chill Advisory, from 9 PM this evening to
10 AM CST Thursday. For the Winter Storm Watch, from Friday
morning through Saturday afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult Friday and Saturday.
The hazardous conditions could impact the morning and evening
commutes. The cold wind chills could cause frostbite on exposed
skin in as little as 30 minutes.
properties.instruction:
Use caution while traveling outside. Wear appropriate clothing, a
hat, and gloves.

Slow down and use caution while traveling.

Monitor the latest forecasts for updates on this situation.

The latest road conditions can be obtained by calling 5 1 1.
Road conditions can also be found at 511mn.org for Minnesota or
511wi.gov for Wisconsin.
